title: For Sale:  Reply to FS: 22lr
postcontent:
I am not that seller but do buy/sell on here and GunBroker I realize you are upset as everyone else is. Basic supply and demand though. Shipments are delayed until 2014 for cases and there is no sign of let-up in demand. 

Look at Cheaper than Dirt and all the stores online selling what they have for $0.50/round and up and you blame this guy for sharing his stash? I have only a certain limit, dependent on the market, that I am willing to sell for. I stocked up ahead yet due to shooting a lot  I sold off all the crap I didn't want so I could get needed stuff for SHTF. If I pay an arm and a leg on GunBroker for a bulk of ammo then sell the rest on here at least others get ammo and you have to figure in shipping and time spend searching/bidding like mad and the standing in line/gas for money orders or ripped for PayPal. 

Honestly anyone can make a ton more on GunBroker but it is more work. You have to make up for gas way the F out to FedEx on Manitou or UPS on Central as they are the only places to ship ORM-D and deal with standing in line with rude customer service and box everything up, etc. and all the time you spend doing it. Non-payers suck too.

Basically everyone is hurting. I've personally sold ammo at or just above what I have paid, especially to repeat buyers. So suck it up, it is the new norm. Saw less than 10 boxes of .22 at the gunshow...they can charge whatever they want. If you need it bad enough you'll pay. 

See you in the FEMA "Re-Education Camp!"

title: For Sale:  Century Arms Sterling Sporter by Wise Lite Arms (w/ 5 mags)
postcontent:
If you're having a hard time finding a Kel-Tec Sub2000, Marlin Camp9 or other 9mm carbine, take a look at this nice little gun.  It's a Sterling Sporter that was sold by Century Arms International.  Made in the U.S.A. by Wise Lite Arms out of Boyd, TX.  

It shoots regular 9mm and has a folding collapsable stock.  The recoil is so minimal, it's like shooting a 22lr.  It is based off of the British Sterling sub machine gun that has a rich history of fighting bad guys all over the world.  Wise Lite modifies the bolts for semi-auto and lengthens the gun so that it is fully legal.  With not much effort at all, one could turn this thing into a great little SBR.

The gun is practically brand new.  I have fired less than 100 rounds total through it on a couple of ocassions.  It's a fun little gun.

The gun comes with 5 (yes 5) 34-round magazines.  These are not always the easiest to find and they go for $40+ on the online broker sites.  Speaking of magazines, these just might be the best magazines you will ever come across.  They have a follower that has built in rollers to aid in loading.  The 34th round loads as easy as the first round.  And they are incredibly easy to disassemble and clean.

It also comes with a spare firing pin that I bought directly from Wise Lite, just in case I ever needed it.

If you're a Star Wars fan and you think the gun looks familiar, you're not crazy.  This gun is the basis for the guns used by the Storm Troopers.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington Sportsman 48 12 ga Auto loading shotgun
postcontent:
Great gun, bluing is nice and works perfectly.  The forearm does have a chunk missing but in no way hinders the handling or performance.  I have too many shotguns.  Values on this gun are around $250.  You can get a new forearm for around $40.  I think $150 is a very good price.  I would like to trade or partial trade for a .50 cal muzzle loader. Or cash.
FOID card is a must and bill of sale.

Design

The 11-48 is a long-recoil operated semi-automatic shotgun based on the Remington Model 11. Shells are stored in a tubular magazine under the barrel. When a chambered shell is fired, the barrel and bolt recoiling together (for a distance greater than the shell length) re-cock the hammer, eject the spent shell, and feed another shell from the magazine into the action.
The 11-48 differs from the Model 11 in the shape of its machined steel receiver and the use of cheaper stamped steel internal parts. The new easily removable aluminum trigger housing was to be featured on its successors, the 1100 and the 11-87.
Like the Model 11, the gun operated by way of two return springs. The first, located in the buttstock, serves as the resistance to the bolt. The second spring, located over the magazine tube, serves as the barrel recoil spring, allowing the barrel to recoil several inches into the receiver. The 11-48 differs from the Model 11 in the friction ring placed at the forward end of the barrel recoil spring. The Model 11 had a brass friction ring with one blunt end and one beveled end. The ring fit into a corresponding cut in the barrel underlug. For heavy loads, the ring was turned with the beveled end facing the lug. For lighter loads, the blunt end was turned to face the lug. The 11-48 features a similar friction ring system but is modified to be self-adjusting so as to work with all loads.
[edit]Sportsman '48

The Sportsman '48 is a variation introduced to comply with various US hunting laws. It came with a crimped magazine tube that allowed it to be loaded with only 2 shells in the magazine. One additional round placed in the chamber brought its total capacity to three shells. It came in 12, 16, and 20 gauge variations.

About 120 rounds through the rifle. All russian made. This would be perfect as a stand alone or a custom build gun.  Vepr's are knowns as being some of the nicest and most accurate Ak's made.  This model also comes with the more rare 20.5" barrel for increased accuracy and bullet velocity.  Unlike many Ak's Vepr's have a lifetime warranty.  Included are 2 magazines. This firearm is built on the same standard as the RPK style machine guns, Vepr is 50% more reinforced than a standard, stamped AK rifle.  This makes this one of the most accurate AK's you can buy.  Each rifle has been manufactured using state of the art technology, effectively creating a heavier duty piece that will last through not just a lifetime but for many generations to come. The VEPR is simply the highest quality rifle based on the Kalashnikov design. The VEPR Rifles and Carbines are sporting arms based on the famous Soviet designed RPK. postcontent:
MASA Firearms is a family owned (father and son) firearm sales and training facility. We have the inventory the other guys don't. Whether you're an expert shot, or a complete novice with no experience at all, we cater to your individual needs. We encourage you to stop in and experience the MASA Firearms difference. MASA FIREARMS
11070 Wiles Rd.

954.805.3440

SUPRISINGLY SLIM. One of the most anticipated handguns to come along in a long time is the new Springfield XDs, single-stack .45ACP pistol. Why all the excitement? Simple. The Springfield XDs is THE quentissential single-stack, ultra- compact concealed carry .45 that shooters have been waiting for. There are a great many 9mm and .40S&W ultra-compacts on the market today, but the Springfield XDs .45ACP is in a league of its own. With so many Texans getting concealed carry licenses, there is a huge demand for small, concealable handguns that can stop an attacker.

The short barrel—while making the gun easy to carry—will be criticized by some as “sacrificing velocity.” The .45 however, does its work by mass and diameter, not by speed. What may be lost in terms of velocity in a shorter barrel will be more than made up by the .45's greater stopping power.

Even though the manufacturers specs will give you a small glimpse into its overall dimensions, you really have to hold a Springfield XDs to appreciate how compact and slick it is. Springfield built the XDs around a five-round single-stack magazine and the resulting frame is amazingly easy to wrap your hand around. It has interchangeable backstraps and the result is to change the pitch in your hand, not make it bigger and/or bulkier. The compact grip of the Springfield XDs also makes concealed carry easier, as the shorter frame is less likely to print under your shirt or jacket. Perhaps the greatest feature of the XDs, and the one that sets it apart from other compact .45's like the Glock 36, is its manual, 1911 style grip safety.

The Springfield XDs weighs in at only 21.5 oz, and that's light for such a powerful micro pistol chambered in .45ACP. Part of the lightness comes from the polymer frame. The XDs frame has aggressive checkering for a secure grip. The barrel is only 3.3" long - about as small as you can get and still have a gun work reliably in .45 caliber. Overall height of the gun is only 4.4", with an overall length of 6.3", and the width is only 1" - we're talking EXTREMELY concealable.

You might expect a small .45 handgun like the Springfield XDs to be hard to control, yet recoil is suprisingly modest for this micro compact powerhouse. In addition, the XDs will feed a wide range of .45 loads and is accurate to boot. While the Springfield XDs is supplied with two- 5 round magazines, there is an option to purchase an extended magazine that holds 7 rounds. The advantage to such an extended magazine becomes apparent during concealed carry inside the waistband. The extended magazine converts the Springfield XDs into a full grip that is comfortable for even big hands. In addition, the extended mag comes with slide on bottoms to match the two different interchangeable backstrap profiles.
